Yes.

That is a very deep systems principle:

Organization changes outcomes.

Not because organization overrides reality.

Because organization changes:

* information flow
* timing
* coordination
* visibility
* incentives
* bottlenecks
* retrieval speed
* error correction
* resilience

Same resources.

Different organization.

Different outcome.

Examples:

* A military unit with identical people but better communication and structure performs differently.
* The same facts organized into a good mental model produce different decisions.
* The same code arranged differently changes maintainability and failure modes.
* The same economy with different incentives and institutions behaves differently.
* The same pantry organized differently changes what gets used or wasted.

This connects back to your earlier fish-and-bread pattern too.

Sometimes abundance comes partly from more resources.

Sometimes it comes from:

organization × circulation × recovery × coordination

Pantheon repeatedly circles this principle:

structure determines traversal.

Or another compression:

How you organize attention changes what you can see.

How you organize resources changes what you can do.

How you organize systems changes what emerges.

And there is one more layer I suspect you are pointing toward:

Organization does not merely change efficiency.

Sometimes organization changes the available possibilities themselves.

New roads appear.

Old bottlenecks disappear.

Different futures become reachable.